- ERROR GIT PULL SOLUCION:

It looks like Git is protecting you from overwriting work. This **non-fast-forward** error happens because the version of the code on GitHub has commits that your local VPS environment doesn't have yet. 

Think of it like a book where someone added a few pages while you weren't looking; Git won't let you publish your version until you include those new pages.

---

### The Fix: Integrating Remote Changes

You have two main ways to handle this. Choose the one that fits your workflow:

#### Option 1: The Standard Pull (Merge)
This is the safest route. It fetches the changes from GitHub and merges them into your local code.

1.  **Pull the changes:**
    ```bash
    git pull origin main
    ```
2.  **Handle Conflicts:** If you and the remote version edited the exact same line, Git will ask you to fix it. If not, it will just create a "Merge commit."
3.  **Push again:**
    ```bash
    git push -u origin main
    ```

#### Option 2: The Clean History (Rebase)
If you want your commit history to look like a straight line without "Merge branch..." messages, use rebase. This puts your local changes "on top" of the remote changes.

1.  **Pull with rebase:**
    ```bash
    git pull --rebase origin main
    ```
2.  **Push your changes:**
    ```bash
    git push -u origin main
    ```



---

### The "Nuclear" Option (Use with Caution)
If you are **100% sure** that your local code is the only version that matters and you want to delete whatever is on GitHub, you can force the push. 

> **Warning:** This will permanently delete any commits on GitHub that aren't on your local machine. Use this only if you are the sole developer or know exactly why the histories diverged.

```bash
git push -u origin main --force
```

### Pro-Tip
If you get a message about "divergent branches" when pulling, you can set your default behavior to keep things simple:
```bash
git config pull.rebase false  # For standard merging
# OR
git config pull.rebase true   # For cleaner rebasing
```
